{"TopicId":144484,"ForumId":20,"TopicTitle":"Auto-lights at night","CreatedByName":"DJ Reonic","CreatedById":161437,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-24T22:27:38Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"DJ Reonic","CreatedById":161437,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-24T22:27:38Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAre there any mods out there that include the ability to set lights to activate when a ship or station goes into a planet\u0027s shadow? I\u0027ve been looking, but have yet to find one.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"genericeventhandler","CreatedById":149557,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T13:05:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI don\u0027t know if it\u0027s possible, I\u0027ll have a look to see if I can figure it out.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"DJ Reonic","CreatedById":161437,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T13:19:50Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI know solar panels have a mechanic for detecting sunlight exposure, so maybe that mechanic could be used to activate the lights. (if Sun exposure = 0, then activate lights) or something like that. If I had the time, I\u0027d take a crack at it myself. Thanks for looking into it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"genericeventhandler","CreatedById":149557,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T13:29:32Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSolar panels, wouldn\u0027t work, that was my first thought, panels obscured would think it was night.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI suppose you could look at the increase in Electriccharge,\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0but even that is tricky, how do you decide if you are in darkness? \u00A0charge is negative, In sunlight charge is positive.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI might try this.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nif \u00A0charge is negative and ec \u0026gt; 25% turn on lights\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nif charge is negative and ec \u0026lt; 25% turn off lights (to conserve power)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nif charge is positive and ec \u0026gt; 25% turn off lights ( in sunlight )\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOf course that doesn\u0027t account for \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Radio-isotope Thermo-electric Generator (a.k.a. Mars rover heating device)\u0022\u003ERTG\u003C/abbr\u003E\u0027s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe other alternative, is to make a light that has a solar panel attached, if the solar panel has flow turn the light off, if it doesn\u0027t turn the light on.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBut that requires creating a special part, and that I\u0027m no good at. I\u0027ll try the module thing though.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-07-25T13:34:06Z\u0022 title=\u002207/25/2016 01:34  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EJuly 25, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by genericeventhandler\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Alshain","CreatedById":110959,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T15:51:38Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe issue with the inverted solar panel design is that solar panel activity occurs based on craft orientation and occlusion, not just which side of the planet you are on.\u00A0\u00A0 That means lights could turn on even on the light side of the planet, depending on craft orientation.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYou would have to develop occlusion detection between the sun and the craft, which is possible but it\u0027s not as simple as re-using existing code in the game.\u00A0 The various antenna mods do this to determine connectivity, so rest assured it is possible if someone is willing to attempt it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-07-25T15:52:08Z\u0022 title=\u002207/25/2016 03:52  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EJuly 25, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by Alshain\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"genericeventhandler","CreatedById":149557,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T16:41:26Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222690458\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022144484\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221469461898\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022110959\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Alshain\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n49 minutes ago, Alshain said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe issue with the inverted solar panel design is that solar panel activity occurs based on craft orientation and occlusion, not just which side of the planet you are on.\u00A0\u00A0 That means lights could turn on even on the light side of the planet, depending on craft orientation.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYou would have to develop occlusion detection between the sun and the craft, which is possible but it\u0027s not as simple as re-using existing code in the game.\u00A0 The various antenna mods do this to determine connectivity, so rest assured it is possible if someone is willing to attempt it.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI quite like the idea of individual occluded lights turning on though, \u00A0sometimes it\u0027s tricky doing eva with the sun behind the craft.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"AlmostNASA","CreatedById":158711,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T16:51:53Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222689663\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022144484\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221469399258\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022161437\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022DJ Reonic\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n18 hours ago, DJ Reonic said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAre there any mods out there that include the ability to set lights to activate when a ship or station goes into a planet\u0027s shadow? I\u0027ve been looking, but have yet to find one.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt\u0027s called planetshine so basically you have light when you are in the dark side but you might want to adjust the light levels.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Alshain","CreatedById":110959,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-25T17:26:59Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222690537\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022144484\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221469465513\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022158711\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022AlmostNASA\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n35 minutes ago, AlmostNASA said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt\u0027s called planetshine so basically you have light when you are in the dark side but you might want to adjust the light levels.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nPlanetShine doesn\u0027t do that.\u00A0 PlanetShine renders reflected light from the daylight side of the planet (on the side of the craft facing the planet).\u00A0 It\u0027s a good mod but it doesn\u0027t generate light on the dark side of the planet.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222016-07-25T17:27:24Z\u0022 title=\u002207/25/2016 05:27  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00227 yr\u0022\u003EJuly 25, 2016\u003C/time\u003E by Alshain\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sarbian","CreatedById":57146,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-26T12:07:48Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe solar panel idea works fine, you just need to do your raytrace with the proper layer mask to ignore the ship parts.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"ShotgunNinja","CreatedById":159391,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-07-26T17:46:08Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf you want you can use these two functions\u00A0for the raytracing:\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler\u0022 data-ipsspoiler=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_header\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003ESpoiler\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsSpoiler_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cpre class=\u0022ipsCode prettyprint prettyprinted\u0022\u003E\n\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// return true if the ray \u0027dir\u0027 starting at \u0027p\u0027 doesn\u0027t hit \u0027body\u0027\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// - p: ray origin\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// - dir: ray direction\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// - body: obstacle\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Epublic\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Estatic\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Ebool\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ERaytrace\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E(\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EVector3d\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E p\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E,\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EVector3d\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E dir\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E,\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ECelestialBody\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E body\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E)\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E{\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// ray from origin to body center\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EVector3d\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E diff \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E=\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E body\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003Eposition \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E-\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E p\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E;\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// projection of origin-\u0026gt;body center ray over the raytracing direction\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Edouble\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E k \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E=\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EVector3d\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EDot\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E(\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003Ediff\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E,\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E dir\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E);\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022com\u0022\u003E// the ray doesn\u0027t hit body if its minimal analytical distance along the ray is less than its radius\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\n  \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Ereturn\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E k \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E\u0026lt;\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022lit\u0022\u003E0.0\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E||\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E(\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003Edir \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E*\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E k \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E-\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E diff\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E).\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003Emagnitude \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E\u0026gt;\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E body\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ERadius\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u